taxonomicNotes: Regional differences between male colour patterns suggest there may be distinct populations or subspecies (Norman 2003). Individuals from the east and southern coast show both genetic and morphological differences that suggest previous isolation and subsequent secondary contact to form a continuous distribution (Reid et al. 2005).  It has been suggested that the Spencer Gulf population may represent a separate species (Bronwyn Gillanders pers. comm. 2010).

This species was described as Cirroctopus hochbergi O'Shea 1999 from off New Zealand (Type locality 39 58.9'S, 178 14.27'E, 800-1070 m). It is most similar to Cirroctopus mawsoni, but a few characters separate it and it is 'strongly allopatric' (O'Shea 1999).
Uthicke et al. (2004) by genetic analysis differentiated Holothuria whitmaei, H. fuscogilva and H. nobilis that were previously confused.
The genus Isopora was previously a subgenus but was elevated (Wallace et al. 2007).
This species is sometimes confused with the similar A. downingi (Riegl et al. 2012).

There remains some confusion regarding the valid name of this nominal species. In a review of the staghorn corals, Wallace (1999) considered A. formosa to be a junior synonym of A. muricata. Currently, A. formosa is not valid in WoRMS (Hoeksema and Cairns 2019) or Corals of the World (Veron et al. 2016). Therefore, this species will be assessed as A. muricata. Additionally, Acropora copiosa is considered a junior synonym of this species,  A. muricata (Hoeksema and Cairns 2020).
